I have stage 3A colon cancer. I was diagnosed in March 2023 and had colon resection surgery in May 2023.  I caught it during a colonoscopy (my first), but unfortunately there was spread to a nearby lymph node. Mind you, I had no symptoms indicating cancer at all.

There is so much to say about my cancer journey as I am still going through it, taking it one day at a time.  I will share more along the way.

My father passed away from colorectal cancer. Even though I did my colonoscopy early, I should have done it even sooner. But I was young, healthy, and I didn’t want to go through the prep. I opted to do a stool sample instead which came out clean. I put off my colonoscopy for a few years.  Had I done my colonoscopy back then, I probably would’ve seen the cancer a few years ago. But I didn’t.

I decided to share this publicly because when I shared my diagnosis with close friends, many of them told me they had just cancelled their colonoscopies because it was inconvenient!  Cancer isn’t preventable, it’s all about EARLY DETECTION. Yes, it’s inconvenient but guess what, cancer is 10000x more inconvenient. This can SAVE YOUR LIFE.

Thank you to my doctors and nurses at @keckmedicineusc @uscnorriscancercenter, prayers from the prayer team @marinerschurch + @ericbgeiger, MY VILLAGE, MY PEOPLE, you know who you are 🫶🏼

Intermittent fasting is not for weight loss!  Many people do it to lose weight but the benefits of intermittent fasting go way beyond the scale. Read below for mind blowing data.

After getting my cancer diagnosis, I immediately began researching natural ways to fight cancer. I came across @drericberg YouTube videos and immediately began intermittent fasting.

I’m not a doctor, not in the medical field at all, but these are what the data shows. When I had my colonoscopy, my tumor was 6 cm in size. After a month of fasting for 18 hours per day plus doing a 24 hr fast once a week, by the time I had my surgery, my TUMOR SHRUNK to 3.8 cm! I can’t believe that was a just coincidence.

I not only fasted, but when I ate, it was a diet full of CRUCIFEROUS VEGETABLES. There is so much data behind fasting and how beneficial cruciferous vegetables are for cancer!

Benefits of IF:

- Repairs cells and removes waste (autophagy)
- Changes genes and molecules to protect against disease
- Reduces insulin levels + human growth hormones increase
- Reduces oxidative stress + inflammation
- Can prevent cancer + reduce side effects of chemotherapy

Cancer fighting elements in cruciferous vegetables:

- Glucosinolates (inhibits cancer enzymes + protects against inflammatory disease)
- Folate/ B-9 (promotes cell growth + function)
- Flavonols (reduces vascular disease)
- Dietary fiber (normalized bowl movements + lowers cholesterol)

I am officially halfway through my chemo treatment!! Cycle 2 out of 4 done! 🎉

The decision on which chemo treatment was best for me wasn’t an easy one. Neither sounded better than the other.  I decided to do the 3 month, slightly more aggressive treatment, but half the time compared to the other option, and advocated for no port or PICC line for myself.

The 3 month treatment (CAPOX) consists of 4 cycles, each 3 weeks apart. An infusion on Day 1 followed by 14 days of chemo pills at home, twice a day, then one week off of everything before the cycle starts again.

So far, I can’t complain. The week of the infusion is the hardest on me with loss of appetite, nausea, headaches, light sensitivity, first bite pain, and more. Overall I think my body has been handling it well bc there are more good days than bad.

With every infusion I wear gloves and socks with ice packs to help prevent neuropathy in my hands and feet (a numbness + tingling side effect from chemo). I’ve also added other natural supplements to my routine to help get ahead of side effects. I don’t know which one is working or what is helping the best, but I know they’re doing something and I will continue to do what I’m doing because I am grateful for how my body is handling this all.

- Meningitis B is an uncommon, but potentially serious illness that can cause life-threatening complications and death.
- While anyone can get meningitis, those who are in their late teens and early adulthood, 16 - 23, are one of the age groups most affected.
- It can spread through certain common behaviors such as living in close quarters, coughing, sneezing, kissing, and sharing drinks or utensils.
